print ("Let's move on.")
print ("Conditional statements allow a program to make decisions based on whether a condition is true or false.")
print (" The most common ones are if, else if (called elif in Python), and else. ")
print ("An if statement runs a block of code only when its condition is true. If that condition is false, the program can check another condition using elif, and if none of the conditions are true, the else block runs. ")
print ("These statements rely on comparison and logical operators and are essential for controlling the flow of a program, such as deciding whether a student passed an exam or whether a user can access a feature.")

print ("Loops are used to repeat a block of code multiple times without rewriting it.")
print (" A for loop is typically used when you know how many times you want the loop to run, such as looping through a list of values or repeating an action a fixed number of times. ")
print (" The loop runs once for each item in a sequence, executing the same code each time with a different value. ")
print (" This makes for loops especially useful for processing collections like lists, tuples, or sets.")

print ("A while loop continues running as long as a given condition remains true. ")
print ("Unlike a for loop, a while loop is used when the number of repetitions is not known in advance, such as waiting for valid user input or repeating an action until a goal is met. ")
print ("Because while loops depend on conditions, it is important to update the condition inside the loop; otherwise, the program may run forever in what is called an infinite loop. ")
print ("Together, conditionals and loops allow programs to make decisions, repeat tasks efficiently, and respond dynamically to different situations.")
